**Arduino sketch:**

```cpp
#include <Arduino.h>

unsigned long last = 0;

void setup() { Serial.begin(115200); }

void loop() {
  unsigned long now = millis();
  if (now - last >= 1000) {
    last = now;
    Serial.print("uptime ms: ");
    Serial.println(now);
  }
}
```

**conduyt-js host:**

```ts
const start = Date.now()
setInterval(() => {
  console.log('host uptime ms:', Date.now() - start)
}, 1000)
```

millis() returns the chip's uptime in milliseconds. It is an Arduino primitive and does not exist in JavaScript. JavaScript uses Date.now() (epoch ms) or performance.now() (monotonic, sub-ms).

**Arduino (Adafruit_NeoPixel):**

```cpp
#include <Arduino.h>
#include <Adafruit_NeoPixel.h>

const int PIXEL_PIN = 6;
const int PIXEL_COUNT = 30;
Adafruit_NeoPixel strip(PIXEL_COUNT, PIXEL_PIN, NEO_GRB + NEO_KHZ800);

uint32_t wheel(byte p) {
  p = 255 - p;
  if (p < 85)  return strip.Color(255 - p * 3, 0, p * 3);
  if (p < 170) { p -= 85;  return strip.Color(0, p * 3, 255 - p * 3); }
  p -= 170;     return strip.Color(p * 3, 255 - p * 3, 0);
}

void setup() { strip.begin(); strip.setBrightness(40); }

void loop() {
  static uint16_t j = 0;
  for (int i = 0; i < PIXEL_COUNT; i++)
    strip.setPixelColor(i, wheel(((i * 256 / PIXEL_COUNT) + j) & 255));
  strip.show();
  j = (j + 1) & 255;
  delay(20);
}
```

**conduyt-js (ConduytNeoPixel module):**

```ts
import { ConduytDevice } from 'conduyt-js'
import { SerialTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/serial'
import { ConduytNeoPixel } from 'conduyt-js/modules/neopixel'

const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(
  new SerialTransport({ path: '/dev/ttyACM0' })
)

const strip = new ConduytNeoPixel(device)
await strip.begin(6, 30)
await strip.setBrightness(40)

function wheel(pos: number): [number, number, number] {
  pos = (255 - pos) & 255
  if (pos < 85)  return [255 - pos * 3, 0, pos * 3]
  if (pos < 170) { pos -= 85;  return [0, pos * 3, 255 - pos * 3] }
  pos -= 170;     return [pos * 3, 255 - pos * 3, 0]
}

let j = 0
while (true) {
  for (let i = 0; i < 30; i++) {
    const [r, g, b] = wheel(((i * 256 / 30) + j) & 255)
    await strip.setPixel(i, r, g, b)
  }
  await strip.show()
  j = (j + 1) & 255
  await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 20))
}
```

**Arduino sketch (hardware ISR via attachInterrupt):**

```cpp
#include <Arduino.h>

const int PULSE_PIN = 2;
volatile unsigned long count = 0;

void onRise() { count++; }

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  pinMode(PULSE_PIN, INPUT);
  attachInterrupt(digitalPinToInterrupt(PULSE_PIN), onRise, RISING);
}

void loop() {
  static unsigned long last = 0;
  if (millis() - last >= 1000) {
    last = millis();
    noInterrupts();
    unsigned long c = count;
    count = 0;
    interrupts();
    Serial.print("Hz: ");
    Serial.println(c);
  }
}
```

**conduyt-js (firmware-side ISR, host subscribes):**

```ts
import { ConduytDevice, SUB_MODE } from 'conduyt-js'
import { SerialTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/serial'

const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(
  new SerialTransport({ path: '/dev/ttyACM0' })
)

await device.pin(2).mode('input')

let count = 0
;(async () => {
  for await (const _ of device.pin(2).subscribe({ mode: SUB_MODE.RISING })) {
    count++
  }
})()

setInterval(() => {
  console.log('Hz:', count)
  count = 0
}, 1000)
```

Both versions wire an ISR on the chip. In the Arduino sketch the ISR runs C code on the chip. With conduyt-js the firmware runs the ISR and emits a SUB_EVT packet to the host on each edge.

**Arduino (Adafruit_SSD1306):**

```cpp
#include <Arduino.h>
#include <Wire.h>
#include <Adafruit_SSD1306.h>

const int OLED_W = 128;
const int OLED_H = 64;
Adafruit_SSD1306 display(OLED_W, OLED_H, &Wire);

void setup() {
  Wire.begin();
  if (!display.begin(SSD1306_SWITCHCAPVCC, 0x3C)) {
    while (true) {}
  }
  display.clearDisplay();
  display.setTextSize(2);
  display.setTextColor(SSD1306_WHITE);
  display.setCursor(0, 24);
  display.println("hello");
  display.display();
}

void loop() {}
```

**conduyt-js (ConduytOLED module):**

```ts
import { ConduytDevice } from 'conduyt-js'
import { SerialTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/serial'
import { ConduytOLED } from 'conduyt-js/modules/oled'

const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(
  new SerialTransport({ path: '/dev/ttyACM0' })
)

const oled = new ConduytOLED(device)
await oled.begin({ width: 128, height: 64, address: 0x3C })
await oled.clear()
await oled.text(0, 24, 'hello', { size: 2 })
await oled.show()
```

The Arduino sketch joins a WiFi AP from the chip. The conduyt-js host already lives on the network; it talks to the device over serial or BLE for hardware, and uses normal Node networking for HTTP.

**Arduino sketch (chip-side WiFi):**

```cpp
#include <Arduino.h>
#include <WiFi.h>
#include <HTTPClient.h>

const char* SSID = "yourSSID";
const char* PASS = "yourPass";

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(115200);
  WiFi.begin(SSID, PASS);
  while (WiFi.status() != WL_CONNECTED) delay(250);
  HTTPClient http;
  http.begin("https://example.com/health");
  Serial.println(http.GET());
  http.end();
}

void loop() {}
```

**conduyt-js (host has internet, device is just hardware):**

```ts
import { ConduytDevice } from 'conduyt-js'
import { SerialTransport } from 'conduyt-js/transports/serial'

const device = await ConduytDevice.connect(
  new SerialTransport({ path: '/dev/ttyACM0' })
)

const status = await fetch('https://example.com/health').then(r => r.status)
console.log('status', status)
console.log('A0', await device.pin('A0').read())
```

This is the cleanest split: ESP32 handles hardware over CONDUYT, the host handles HTTP.

**Arduino (Adafruit DHT):**

```cpp
#include <Arduino.h>
#include <DHT.h>

const int DHT_PIN = 4;
DHT dht(DHT_PIN, DHT22);

void setup() { Serial.begin(115200); dht.begin(); }

void loop() {
  float t = dht.readTemperature();
  float h = dht.readHumidity();
  if (!isnan(t) && !isnan(h)) {
    Serial.print("T="); Serial.print(t, 1);
    Serial.print(" RH="); Serial.println(h, 1);
  }
  delay(2000);
}
```

